We must “build” the accounts‐payable line by adding up the “credit purchases” – that is, only the Purchase transactions that have not been paid (actually being “unpaid” and using the “Account Payable” payment method). (When a purchase is paid by another method – say “Bank Transfer” or “Cash” – it is paid immediately and does not leave a liability.) 

Looking carefully at the data (only the rows whose “type” is Purchase and whose “payment/receipt_status” is Unpaid and “payment_method” is “Account Payable”) we find the following rows (with their “amount” values):

• Purchase20231231006: 100000.0  
• Purchase20231231010: 300000.0  
• Purchase20231231013: 1000.0  
• Purchase20231231014: 15000.0  
• Purchase20231231018: 60000.0  
• Purchase20231231024: 20000.0  
• Purchase20231231025: 5000.0  
• Purchase20231231026: 300000.0  
• Purchase20231231029: 15000.0  

We now add these amounts step‐by‐step:
  100000.0 + 300000.0 = 400000.0  
  400000.0 + 1000.0 = 401000.0  
  401000.0 + 15000.0 = 416000.0  
  416000.0 + 60000.0 = 476000.0  
  476000.0 + 20000.0 = 496000.0  
  496000.0 + 5000.0 = 501000.0  
  501000.0 + 300000.0 = 801000.0  
  801000.0 + 15000.0 = 816000.0  

There are no offsets (that is, no “paid” transactions that specifically reduce an outstanding accounts payable balance – all such purchases are recorded only when they are “unpaid”).

Thus the net (increase in) accounts payable is 816,000.00.
